  "target_response": {
    "text": "Your metabolism isn't broken — a two-week flat patch is a normal chapter in steady weight loss. Day-to-day scale weight is dominated by water: sodium, carbohydrate stores, training stress and cycle timing can each hide real fat loss for a couple of weeks at a time. There's also a genuine but modest effect where maintenance needs shrink slightly as you get lighter, which slowly narrows a fixed deficit. What to do: change nothing for another two weeks, keep the same intake and training, and judge by the weekly average of morning weigh-ins. If that average is still flat after the extra fortnight, trim intake slightly or add a little easy activity — a small nudge, not a slash. Most plateaus at your stage resolve on their own before the nudge is even needed.",
